            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe remembers being ten, perched on a stack of flattened cardboard boxes in the back of the store. The air smelled of ginger and dusty cement. With a stubby pencil, she sketched a flowing silk gown onto a torn grocery bag, a secret world of elegance amidst her parents\u2019 pragmatism. It wasn't just drawing; it was an act of quiet defiance. This was the first place she built that was entirely her own, a skill she would need to protect her dream from her parents\u2019 well-meaning worries.\n\n2.\nThe first time she truly felt the power of her work was on the sales floor in her early twenties. An older woman was fretful, convinced nothing would look right for her son's wedding. Christina gently ignored the woman's self-criticism, instead pulling a simple, perfectly cut sheath dress in a deep sapphire. In the fitting room mirror, the woman\u2019s posture changed. She stood taller, her eyes welling with tears. In that moment, Christina understood her calling wasn't just about fashion, but about helping women see themselves again.\n\n3.\nThe dot-com bust was a brutal time, for the city and for her. She recalls the quiet finality of signing her divorce papers at their small dining room table. There was no anger, only a shared, heavy sadness. He looked at her, his expression unreadable, and said, \"Go be brilliant, Christina. Just promise me you'll be happy.\" His words weren't a curse, but a blessing. They freed her to pour everything into her career, transforming her ambition from a source of conflict into a promise she had to keep.\n\n4.\nHer first major buying decision felt like a gamble. The economy was tanking, and she was pitching an unknown, expensive handbag line from Paris. The numbers were tight, her forecast audacious. When the entire stock sold out in a week, her boss, a famously stoic man, didn't congratulate her. He simply caught her eye across the office and gave a single, sharp nod. That silent acknowledgment felt more validating than any bonus, cementing her reputation for making smart choices under immense pressure and teaching her to trust her gut.\n\n5.\nLast year in Milan, exhausted after a tense vendor meeting, she stumbled into a tiny, hidden boutique. Inside, a young Taiwanese designer was meticulously hand-stitching a label into a linen jacket. The intense, personal care in that one small gesture struck Christina with incredible force. It felt more luxurious than anything in the grand showrooms she frequented. On the MUNI back home, the seed of an idea\u2014her own store, her own legacy\u2014fully took root, a perfect, full-circle synthesis of the girl in the stockroom and the woman she\u2019d become."
